originalText:
::He observes you with caution, panting heavily while at the same time trying to be as still as possible. He takes his time with his greeting.::

Hi.

::A pair of eyes stare at you, tinted with fearful determination.::

$(context.npc_xpbl_as_todd_playerName_stuttered)!
::Todd brings his right hand near the gate control screen: The red light turns green, ::
::You slow down and start breathing heavily - fatigue has set in. Todd wastes no time breaking free from your weakened hold and making his escape.::
Oh, um, I can't talk now, I-I-I have to exercise.
::He whispers, furtively looking at Seeger.:: This man's hair scares me. But he lets me play games.
::He whispers, making sure that Donnie can't hear him; there is great geniality and confidence in his voice.:: He's short!
::He says while putting down a piece of rusted metal covered in varicolored corals.::
Did you find me a new home?
I can only take you to the surface. Then you're on your own.
Sorry, $(#this is a one-man submarine/I like to lift my feet up). ::Attack!::

::and the gate opens. He pauses, almost as if he wishes to turn away and leave, but he instead speaks with a new voice, not too dissimilar to his usual tenor.:: 

Todd?

::He looks around.::
::the gate opens - and Todd takes the opportunity to make his escape.::
::[Wrestling] Drag him to the console and force him to unlock it.::
::[Strength] Drag him to the console and force him to unlock it.::
::[Dirty Kick][Strength] Knee him in the groin, then drag him to the console and force him to unlock it.::

::It takes him some more time to respond.::

Hi.

::It takes him some more time to respond.::

I am. But... but Mother told me to always be polite.

::You find him sitting on the bench, wiping his forehead with the absorbent patch on his sleeve. Then, with gleaming eyes, he opens an unlabeled institutional size can and begins scooping some kind of dark paste from it; its smell is sweet and sour - and distance-keepingly pungent - but he seems to be reveling in the stuff.::
Not yet, Todd. How are you holding up?
Not yet. But I'm working on it. See ya.
::He gathers his courage.:: I want to go with you.
::He swallows a lump in his throat and nods.::
I... ::He gathers his courage.:: want to go with you. I gotta.
::Just before acting you realize you've blocked all of the passages to R&D when you closed those gates; you feel it'd be wiser to open them before forcing Todd into doing anything.::

::He flinches, raising his arms instinctively to shield his face; you grab one, push it up and back with one of your hands while moving to his side and pushing his head down with your other hand.::

Aaaahh!

::From here you simply get behind him and lock his arm behind his back. You can now direct him as you please - and he's bound to comply.::
::He flinches, raising his arms instinctively to shield his face. You grab him by the arm and pull him toward you. ::
::He manages to cup his bells in time to successfully prevent you from making them ring; without delay he pushes you away and flees.::

::He flinches, raising his arms instinctively to shield his face, leaving his lower body exposed. You take this opportunity to drive your knee into his sensitives - and watch as the ultimate pain drains all color from his face.

You then grab him.::

::He freezes in place, staring at you with eyes wide open.::

I...
I... ::He puts the can down.:: I can't talk to you.
I just need a few directions, that's all.
Wait, wait, wait. Why do you have to exercise?
I need some help. It's urgent.
May I speak to your parents?
I'd like to speak to your parents and parents-in-law again.
I need you to unlock the gate to the R&D dome for me.
Hey, do you have a microchip implant in your hand?
Hey, did you see all the people? Did you? Oooh, I could never have imagined there could be *so* many people in the *same* place all at once. So many...

There are so many people here. Did you see that, did you? Oooh, I could never have imagined there could be *so* many people in the *same* place all at once. Some wear very little clothes - especially women. And not only the pretty ones.

He doesn't talk much, uh, the Ferryman. He makes me carry things he brings out of the water. He yelled at me once for breaking something. I was scared of him at first, but then we sat down and he cooked me some strange fish. It was delicious! Then he told me a few stories. He blows so much smoke it hurt my throat. Then we got back to work. 

I am tired, but I feel... good.
Is there a toilet here? I have to pee.
There is no New Lemuria, Todd. You are floating amidst the ruins of the only Lemuria there ever was.
We're getting there, Todd. But first - you.
I've changed my mind. I can't let you go out there all alone.
Yes. Now you're on your own.
This is where you get out.
::He's fighting - using his ample body weight to shake you off - but you manage to hold on. After some back and forth you get a better grip on him and start dragging him toward the R&D gate.::
::He slams into you with his whole body and escapes your grip.::
::In this state it's fairly easy to get a good grip on him and drag him toward the R&D gate.::
::Yet despite his great disadvantage he manages to recover and push you away. After a few first painful steps he manages to run away.::
...will unlock the gate. Move! ::Lead him to the R&D gate.::
This is for your own good. ::Attack!::
I hear F-father coming! I have to go - I have to exercise.
::He furtively glances around and answers with a whisper.:: I need to get in shape and... be more healthy. And be more... um...
I can't go there, I told you!
Research...? No, no, no, no! I can't go there!

::His eyes give you the answer as soon as he looks at his outstretched right hand.::

I, uh...
The old man was nice. We talked a lot about Lemuria. He was nice, but other people look at me strange.

Mr. Grim, he talked to me a lot. He asked me about things. He was nice, but there is something about him I don't like. ::He looks at Donnie.:: But Donnie, he doesn't scare me. I help him reach things because he's short. I haven't dropped anything yet. 

He is pleased. Not because he's short but because I haven't dropped anything.

The Outside... ::He looks up.:: it's so big. Enormous! I can jump as high as I want and not hit my head. I can run freely in this large... *room*, just like my ancestors. And everything is moving, but *really* moving and not like on a screen. 

I can work on something... and do it right. Right - like I used to.

I'm still afraid, though, but I am not alone, no. My family's gone... ::He bows his head.:: but I hope to have a new family. 

I feel... like a new man.

::He looks sadly through the window, observing the illuminated desolation rising above the water surface.::

You lied.
::He smiles, even though he tries to hide it.::

::He looks at the hatch, swallowing a lump in his throat and nervously rubbing his hand against his thigh.::

Through... there?
Yes. I'm... helping $(context.npc_xpbl_as_todd_playerName). And you, are you feeling well? How's our baby boy doing?

::He thinks long about your question.::

I am alive.

::He pauses.:: Todd. My name is Todd.

::He pauses yet again.:: Todd Newman.

::He thinks about his follow-up.:: Nice to-- It's, uh-- 

Nice to meet you, $(#mister/miss).

::He closes his eyes, and the first moments pass in silence. A few twitches ripple across his face, but then he smiles. You wait a while longer until he opens his eyes.::

They are with the Øivindrs... but they say you can join them, $(#Mr./Ms.) Outsider.
::Hoarse falsetto.:: Our guest from New Lemuria.

::Without warning, his tenor voice turns into a high-pitched, hoarse falsetto.::

Todd! Who are you talking to?
But the funny man, the funny man told me I was his favorite, uh... piper! Yes, piper. I don't know what that means, but he was good to me.
::He shakes his head in disgust.:: I'll... I'll go Outside.
Don't be afraid. New Lemuria awaits you.
Don't be afraid. Time to surface.
Just don't touch anything. I'll get the submarine started.
I have to get a few things done first and then we're off. You stay put.

::He pauses.::

But I could tell somehow, I could tell.

This world is dangerous and will swallow you in seconds. You can't take care of yourself, but I can't take care of you either due to the nature of my life. I'll find someone who will, though. You stay here and I'll be back as soon as I find you a new home.
Care for a drink? We have an old bottle of Green Coral. Double distilled. Wonderful, mature spirit.
I talked to your parents. They allow it.
::[Intimidate]:: You're going to unlock the damn gate or else I'm going to rip your arm off and use it myself!
I'm only asking for you to unlock it, not go in there with me.

::Then it drops into bassy rumble.::

By the depths, what is all this commotion? 

::He pauses.:: Who is this person? Who *is* this person, boy?
Good. I gotta go now. See ya.

::He smiles.::

Thank you, $(context.npc_xpbl_as_todd_playerName). I'll stay here. I'll be good. I won't touch anything.

::With some effort and plenty of fear, he opens the hatch and climbs out. 

He shrieks as the hatch falls shut behind him, and panic footsteps pound above your head. 

The last thing you hear is water splashing...::
W-what's the matter, Synna? How's our boy? Don't you... don't you know what I'm talking about? It took us so long, Synna, but we finally did it! You gave me a boy!
I'm looking for something called Acorn. Spelled A-C-o-N-R.
I'm trying to access the R&D dome.
I'm trying to access other domes.
::You wait a few more moments before a voice addresses you...::
::Hoarse falsetto.:: $(context.npc_xpbl_as_todd_playerName), excuse me, ehem, but why are you here exactly? If you understand.
I'd like to know more about you.
Are you really the only ones here? No Servants to help you?
Do you know anything about this thing called the Acorn? Spelled A-C-o-N-R.
Where did you say Acorn might be?
How did Lemuria get its name?
How did Lemuria get its name? Our New Lemurian records have nothing on this.
I'd like to talk to you about Todd.
I have to leave you now.

They do? 

::He pauses, confused.:: 

Yes... they do.

::He shakes his head.::

Mother and F-father told me not to touch it. I can't touch it.
::Tenor.:: Oh, Mother, F-f-father, this is... um... Outsider. $(#He/She) came from...

::Her eyes fill with tears.::

Todd, I'm... dead. Frey is dead. We did not survive the birth.

My parents... *your* parents. Everyone.
When you say station, what do you mean?
Down... ::He looks down.:: no one. Here, there are two families living here: The Newmans and the Øivindrs.
Well... there's me. Would you like to know more about me?
::Baritone.:: Ah. $(#Mr./Ms.) Outsider. So you're the visitor the Newmans have been telling us about.
::He pours some invisible liquid into an invisible glass.::
It's all a part of the Old Lemuria Restoration Project.
I stumbled upon this place by accident.
Actually, I'm just a scavenger. I visit abandoned places, loot what I can find and kill creeps that get in my way.
I'm looking for the Acorn. That thing I asked you about.
I'm looking for something called the Acorn, spelled A-C-o-N-R. Do you know anything about it?
::Hoarse falsetto.:: Anything specific in mind? Would you like to know about the other domes?

::Bass.:: Hmm, well, we'll go first if the Øivindrs don't mind. Where to start...? 

We're descended from the Lemurians which, obviously, found their refuge here. Refuge from... *Biocorp*. ::He utters it with undiluted hatred, clenching his fists and scowling in the process.::
::Baritone.:: Our two families are the only ones here.
::Hoarse falsetto.:: That would be lovely indeed.
::Baritone.:: First you need to know about the Subislanders.
::Baritone.:: Research and Development dome. But it's locked.

::All at once.::

It's a... hm.

::Silence.::

Well, ehem...

You see...
::Bass.:: What did he screw up now?
::He keeps his stare firmly at the gym's exit.::
::He casts a few nervous glances around himself.::
::Bass.:: From the Outside? Is it from the Outside? Speak!

::You don't know whose teary eyes you're staring into, but after a while it doesn't seem to matter.::

You were waiting for me... to make you happy, Synna. For so long. 

You can't be...

::He wipes his tears away.:: You are. 

And I'm alone...
::Gentle falsetto.:: Yes, the one the Newmans have been telling us about.

::Bass.:: Cheers.

::He then raises this imaginary glass, swirls the liquid that's not in it, sniffs its fictitious smell before taking a delightful sip of nothing.::
::Bass.:: Hey! Hope you aren't thinking of taking something of ours, child.
::Hoarse falsetto.:: Well, as you can see, there's plenty of life here. Not as much as it used to, but we're here.

::Hoarse falsetto.:: Ehem, the Newmans were reputable architects, you see. They were the ones who designed Lemuria, and Theodore Newman was the last technology minister. A powerful man who, ehem, surely would've become the prime minister if... things hadn't turned out the way they did.

Meanwhile, I'm a direct descendant of the great composer Kurt Reiluch.
We got to the part about how you imagine the Outside.
::Gentle falsetto.:: That would be us, the Øivindrs.
::Baritone.:: Separation of our two peoples. Unfortunately a violent one.
::Bass.:: By the depths, that's... a tricky one. I think, yes... I think Lemuria means "lost land." Maybe our ancestors rediscovered... whatever it is up there which had been "lost" in the past.

::Hoarse falsetto.:: Angus... *please*. Don't jump to conclusions, dear. I'm sure it's nothing of the sort.

$(context.npc_xpbl_as_todd_playerName), ehem, what did you want to talk to us about?
We'll be here if you wish to
::He gives you a sad and unmistakably more mature look. Then he turns around and jogs away.::
Oh. Well... hm. I've never been asked a question like that...
::He swallows a lump in his throat.::
Well, I'm tired. Really, really tired. I exercise all the time and eat nutrient bars Mother makes me - they're *bleurgh* - but sometimes when I'm really hungry I...
I'll have to correct you there: It's Corporal $(context.player.Name).
Actually, my name is $(context.player.Name). The kid got carried away.
::Baritone.:: And what do you intend to do
::Hoarse falsetto.:: Angus! Of course $(#he/she) won't. $(#He/She) was referring to *abandoned* places.
I'd like to ask you something else.

::Bass.:: Yes, yes. Although, there aren't many family names left anymore. As my father used to say, "Make sons unless you want your last name extinct." ::He even laughs bassily, but then his spirit wanes as his predicament comes into mental foreground.::

::Bass.:: Most Servants were destroyed during the Disunion, and we had no means of replacing certain components for the ones that remained operational. I do manage to activate a strongman from time to time and when need be, but they don't last very long and I have to mix and match working components between them.
::Bass.:: What's there to know, $(context.npc_xpbl_as_todd_playerName) - it's nothing but filthy water.

::Hoarse falsetto.:: I... I like to think all this water is in a large room. Room so large you could spread your arms and run around and not bump into anything. And there is a tower in the middle. A tower with a blue light at the top - I saw that in a painting. Well, maybe Biocorp destroyed it, but then again, maybe they didn't.

::She sighs.:: Biocorp destroys everything...
::Baritone.:: We are the last of our people in Lemuria. Me, my wife - and our daughter Synneva.

::Baritone.:: After the Great War, most prominent Native Lemurians arrived to Abyssal Station - most ministers, their families and everyone else who had been selected. All was well at the start: Biocorp never found this location, and the Natives integrated into the Subislander population well.
I don't know much about it myself, but from my understanding it's a highly valuable piece of technology from before the Great War.
All I know is that it's a pre-Great War technology that's somehow connected to certain machines capable of traversing great distances, even reaching the Surface. That's... beyond Outside.
Never mind. There was something else...
::Hoarse falsetto.:: Ehem, I believe it actually means "*sunken* land." It makes more sense, seeing that we live under water.
Todd seems to be exercising a lot.
Does Todd have a microchip implant in his hand?
Can you let Todd unlock the gate to R&D for me?
Oh! It's a... woman. A young woman.
::Baritone, after taking a sip of nothing himself.:: Splendid.

::Hoarse falsetto.:: Well, there is Docking by the cafeteria, which is where you came from, I suspect. Then there are Manufacturing, Residential One - this one - Residential Two, Food Processing, Aquaponics, Power, and finally - Research and Development.
::Baritone.:: That would be the western exit. But it's locked.

::Bass, while shaking head.:: It is the largest dome, easily three times larger than Docking. There was so much space above your head... ::He smiles.:: so much you could stand on someone's shoulders and still have room above. But it was sealed off after a fire, many years ago, back when I was a boy. 

In those days we could still produce things with the machines that survived the Disunion.
::Hoarse falsetto.:: You came from there, right? Via submarine or a subsphere, right? It is, after all, the station's only connection to the Outside, the place where our
::Hoarse falsetto.:: Why, you're in it right now! This is where we live, all of us. The Øivindrs have their own room, Angus and I our own, and Todd and Synna have their own.

::Hoarse falsetto.:: It is a dome east of here, similar to this one. It leads to Food Processing and Aquaponics. It was slowly abandoned following the Disunion as there weren't many people left at the station.
::Hoarse falsetto, proudly.:: Well, Food Processing and Aquaponics are, ehem, two sections of a single dome, yes. Think of it that way.
::Hoarse falsetto.:: That would be the southern exit. But it's sealed.
::Baritone.:: A fate which befell most Subislanders. Most of our family names were lost due to old family name inheritance laws.

::Hoarse falsetto.:: Yes, yes. We, ehem, used to have a modded handmaiden - Maude. She... had some strongman parts, but only interior. She acted as a nanny of sorts for Todd and Synna, you see, when they were little. Just watched over them and... did simple tasks.
::Baritone.:: Presumably our guest is wondering if we know about what's *above* all of that water, beyond what we can see through our windows or have been told by our grandparents.
::Bass.:: I don't know. My father told me there's no ceiling above the water, but just... one big empty.

There is no land Outside anymore, only water. People live on floating platforms, some of which are at the mercy of the restless waves, some of which can move against them according to their own will and power.

Biocorp destroyed the Outside with their vile weaponry, and few human beings survived the onslaught. There is plenty of land left, but it's dark and lifeless, the only exception to the latter being ravenous beasts with a taste for human flesh.
There is a large doming cavern above the sea, but there is also plenty of land. The land is populated by various groups of people, fighting each other all the time: soldiers, pirates, savages...

The Outside has barely any water left. This is one of the rare places where one needs a submersible to reach the bottom. A large floating light burns the ground so much that people don't come out until its gleam subsides for brief periods of time, and when they do, they fight over drinking water.

The lush reddery has grown out of proportion after Biocorp left and covers both land and water alike. This thorny, poisonous and often carnivorous vegetation makes traveling nearly impossible, so people fly between high towers in which they mostly live. This is not perfectly safe, however, as there are swarms of giant insects in the air, attacking the skyships.

There is no land Outside anymore, only water. People live on floating platforms, some of which are at the mercy of the restless waves, some of which can move against them according to their own will and power. One of these, powered by mighty thrusters and defended by a fleet of warships is the city of New Lemuria.

Biocorp destroyed the Outside with their vile weaponry, and few human beings survived the onslaught. There is plenty of land left, but it's dark and lifeless, the only exception to the latter being ravenous beasts with a taste for human flesh. But amidst this frigid desert there lies the city of light and warmth - New Lemuria.

There is a large doming cavern above the sea, but there is also plenty of land. The land is populated by various groups of people, fighting each other all the time: soldiers, pirates, savages... But far from this conflict, on an island surrounded by high walls and plasma turrets lies a great city - New Lemuria.

The Outside has barely any water left. This is one of the rare places where one needs a submersible to reach the bottom. A large floating light burns the ground so much that people don't come out until its gleam subsides for brief periods of time, and when they do, they fight over drinking water. In a cool shade, built around a tall, mesmerizing waterfall, lies New Lemuria.

The lush reddery has grown out of proportion after Biocorp left and covers both land and water alike. This thorny, poisonous and often carnivorous vegetation makes traveling nearly impossible, so people fly between high towers in which they mostly live. This is not perfectly safe, however, as there are swarms of giant insects in the air, attacking the skyships. The largest tower of all, equipped with laser defenses and wide sky docks is the tower of New Lemuria.
::Hoarse falsetto.:: Synna, ah, sweet, sweet child. Our daughter-in-law.
::Hoarse falsetto.:: The Surface? High Technology? Angus?

::Baritone.:: From my understanding it is, in fact, a "land" or "island" bridge. You must remember, Shelley, that life wasn't always submarine. The bridge could be a symbolic bridge between Native Lemurians' old and new life here.
::Baritone.:: Todd suffers from numerous health problems, both physiological and psychological...
::Hoarse falsetto.:: Yes, of course. We all do.

::A strange thing happens: Todd pauses - Todd, as he appears to have subtly fallen out of character - his mouth moving but no words coming out.

Then...::
::Baritone.:: Unfortunately, no. She can't speak to you.
::Bass.:: What difference does it make, Shelley?
::Bass.:: Leave it, Shelly. A woman wouldn't make a difference anyway.
::Gentle falsetto.:: Unusual name indeed. Asta Øivindr.
::Bass.:: Are you just going to leave and... that's it?
::Hoarse falsetto.:: Are more Outsiders going to come here? Oh, I'd have to clean up the dome...

::Bass.:: By the depths - it was glorious! A network of assembly lines and autobots, which, my father told me, back in his grandfather's day processed materials brought in by sublifters from mining outposts and produced everything we needed, from simple No.1 screws to strongmen and sublifters.

Now... we have nothing. *Nothing*.
ancestors arrived to their future home after being driven out of their former ones by Biocorp - where the war for them ended.
::Baritone.:: We spend nearly all of our time here. I work at the doctor's office, Mr. Newman has his workshop, and my wife works here as well.
::Bass.:: All that free space... But after the boy messed up at the Aquaponics we don't let him go there anymore.

It's where I work. The Aquaponics is a wonderful self-contained, automated system which unifies breeding aquatic life with growing plants - all for our nourishment. And all of this is processed at the other part of the dome - and that is my job. I make sure that what we're eating is up to the highest standards. 

*Ehem*.

::Bass.:: Our power generators are there. 

::He scratches his chin.:: There's no way to repair them if they malfunction; no more spare parts - and the last one who knew how to service them was Shelley's old man - but they do work well, still. That's why we don't want the boy going there.
::Bass.:: Maude... The ol' gal is still around. But I had to deactivate her after she... mmm... malfunctioned.
::Baritone.:: What would you see when you look up?

::Bass, appearing as though he wants to say something else but changes his mind instead.::

The Subislanders came to Lemuria way before the Great War and we've been together since.

::Baritone.:: There was no segregation, and the two peoples lived together, room to room. There was one place where the Natives didn't fit in: The Research and Development dome had two sections: General Laboratories section, and Special Laboratories section. The Special Laboratories performed highly advanced and specialized research, and were composed of respected Atlantean researchers who preferred working their own way and didn't like the outsiders.

Some of these were my great-grandparents, and everything I'm telling you now was passed down through the generations.
::Bass.:: I don't know anything about it, child. Hm, by the depths. If it's important, and if it's here... then it has to be at the Research and Development dome.

::Gentle falsetto.:: I think there is a kind of fish or a crustacean called lemur. These either lived here when your ancestors first came, or were named so because they were bred by Lemurians themselves.
::Hoarse falsetto.:: Life here... it's truly difficult.
::Hoarse falsetto.:: If you don't mind me asking, are they still in use in New Lemuria?

::Bass.:: Yes, yes - about the microchip: You haven't seen the boy use it to open the gate leading to the Research and Development dome, did you? He's forbidden from even looking at it. If you have, tell us. Tell us and I'll...
I... suppose we can trust him to unlock it.
If the boy unlocks it now, what's next? He'll go there and screw something up! Flood the station.
::Gentle falsetto.:: Please speak to my husband.

::He closes his eyes and reopens them after a few moments.:: 

Uh...? Me?
Our daughter Synneva couldn't be present.
::Bass.:: No one goes there. And no one should go to that dome. Curse it to depths.
::Baritone.:: And the same place where yet another war ended.
::Gentle falsetto.:: I work here as well.

::Hoarse falsetto.:: Angus! It was difficult to maintain and the walls have corroded, and the smell - and the filth! We only use the main hallway anyway. ::She shrugs.:: I'd never live there, never ever.

And that, ehem, incident, it could've happened to anyone. Like that fire in Manufacturing, it was... an accident.
::Bass.:: And the boy sent it all to depths. *Single-handedly*.
::Baritone.:: The substation units allow us to monitor and control the power levels. But the hydrothermal generators themselves are made to last.
::Hoarse falsetto.:: Yes, but our family name has, ehem, survived to this day, and so did yours.
::Hoarse falsetto.:: Oh, don't remind me, Angus, don't! Todd couldn't sleep for a week.

::Bass.:: Nothing. All black, I think. Some people were talking about - yeah, I remember it clearly - uh, they were talking about there being a big "natural" light up there, dome-sized - even bigger, but that ought to be the light on the tower Shelley mentioned. It ought to be. 

We all know from experience that if you want light, you have to make a light source. Light doesn't just... shine out of nothing.
::Baritone.:: Yes. Our numbers were modest in the beginning. We came from Atlantis, a station that is said to be in a place called The North, in the direction of the Docking dome but way beyond it.
::Bass.:: That bloody lab... Nrrr - to depths with it!
::Baritone.:: That's where all important technology was brought during the Great War. My ancestors were researchers in the dome, but I've never been told anything about this Acorn.

::All at once.::

Hmmm...

Makes sense.

::Silence.::

Could be...
::Baritone.:: Yes. But the worst of all, Todd has fertility problems.

::Hoarse falsetto.:: You... 

Ehem... ::She smiles at you before turning toward imaginary Angus.::

You have no faith in our son.
But what if, what if--? Eh, well... alright. It can't be that bad.
There could be germs there, viruses - he could get sick! Or if he follows you - hurt himself!
I found this thing in the machine shop.
Can I try the tool bracer on?
I'd like to try out the tool bracer again.
I'll think about all of this. In the meantime...
Hmmm, I have to go. I'll be back soon.
I've seen your family portrait. It's real nice.
I'll think about all of this. In the meantime...
Hmmm, I have to go. I'll be back soon.
I've seen some of Todd's medical records. He's got low testosterone levels. Could that be due to stress?
Let's talk about Todd opening that gate...
I'll think about all of this. In the meantime...
Hmmm, I have to go. I'll be back soon.
::Hoarse falsetto.:: Angus! Don't draw attention to it in front of the visitor!
::Hoarse falsetto.:: Ah, yes... And we're Shelley and Angus Newman. Welcome - and we apologize about... ehem, what you heard during our first encounter, $(context.npc_xpbl_as_todd_playerName).
::Baritone.:: You find it insipid, while to us it is rich, complex and inevitably pleasing to the palate.
::Hoarse falsetto.:: Ehem... yes. Anyway, $(context.npc_xpbl_as_todd_playerName), the dock hasn't been used since those days. Until you arrived... if you... did come that way.
